\title{Embedded languages:\\
  one shell script, four ways to host another language}
\author{Daniel Bosk}
\begin{document}
\maketitle

@ \section{Introduction}

This example is a companion to [[multilang.nw]].  There, every chunk's
language follows from its filename-like \emph{name}.  Here the
interesting chunks have names that say nothing---[[the banner
one-liner]], [[python summary body]]---yet each is written in a
definite language because of \emph{where it is used}.  This is what
[[autolang]] learns to read in Section~\ref{sec:context} of
[[autolang.nw]]: a chunk's language can be imposed by its use site or
by its own first line, not only by its name.

The document is one small shell program, [[summarize]], that prints a
report by hosting Python in three different ways, plus a Makefile that
runs it.  Four chunks get their language from context rather than from
a filename:

\begin{description}
\item[Shebang] [[summarize]] has no extension, but its first line is
  [[#!/bin/sh]], so it is [[bash]].
\item[Interpreter [[-c]]] the banner is a [[python3 -c]] one-liner, so
  its chunk is [[python]].
\item[Here-document, by interpreter] a [[python3 -]] here-document
  feeds Python on standard input, so its body is [[python]].
\item[Here-document, by delimiter] a [[cat]] here-document with the
  delimiter [[PYEOF]] writes a Python file, so its body is [[python]]
  too---read from the delimiter, since [[cat]] names no language.
\item[Make recipe] the Makefile's recipe is factored into a chunk;
  indented under its target it is shell, so it is [[bash]].
\end{description}

The pay-off is in the index: with each chunk labeled, [[autodefs.sh]]
and [[autodefs.python3]] each scan only their own chunks, and
[[autodefs.make]] no longer mistakes a Python [[for]] or [[if]] line
for a Makefile rule.

\section{The script}

[[summarize]] is the root.  Its name is not a filename Pygments
recognises, so without the shebang it would be unlabeled; the
[[#!/bin/sh]] line settles it as shell.

<<[[summarize]]>>=
#!/bin/sh
set -eu
count=$#

<<print the banner>>
<<run the python summary>>
<<write the helper for later>>
@

\subsection{A one-liner through \texttt{python3 -c}}

The banner is one line of Python, passed as the argument of
[[python3 -c]].  Because the chunk sits right after the opening quote
of a [[-c]] argument, it is Python, and [[autodefs.python3]] indexes
the name it binds.

<<print the banner>>=
python3 -c "<<the banner one-liner>>"
<<the banner one-liner>>=
report_banner = "=== deployment report ==="; print(report_banner)
@

\subsection{A here-document on standard input}

The summary is a longer Python program fed to [[python3 -]] on
standard input.  The here-document's body is a chunk of its own,
following the rule that the opening [[<<]] and closing delimiter stay
together in the wrapper while the body chunk holds only the payload.
The interpreter on the opener---[[python3]]---is what marks the body
Python.

<<run the python summary>>=
python3 - "$count" <<'EOF'
<<python summary body>>
EOF
<<python summary body>>=
import sys


def summarize_arguments(argv):
    n = int(argv[1]) if len(argv) > 1 else 0
    for i in range(n):
        if i % 2 == 0:
            print(f"argument {i} is even")
    return n


summarize_arguments(sys.argv)
@

\subsection{A here-document named by its delimiter}

Sometimes the command introducing the here-document is not an
interpreter at all.  Here [[cat]] writes a Python helper to a file for
a later run; [[cat]] names no language, so the body's Python is read
from the delimiter [[PYEOF]] instead---a conventional language tag in
front of the usual [[EOF]].

<<write the helper for later>>=
cat > greet.py <<'PYEOF'
<<the greeter helper>>
PYEOF
<<the greeter helper>>=
def greet(name):
    return f"hello, {name}"


if __name__ == "__main__":
    print(greet("world"))
@

\section{The Makefile}

The Makefile is itself a chunk, named for the file it tangles to, so
[[autolang]] reads it as [[make]] from the name.  Its one recipe is
factored into [[run the report]]: indented by a tab under the target,
that chunk is a shell recipe, so it is labeled [[bash]] and indexed by
[[autodefs.sh]]---not [[autodefs.make]], which would otherwise claim
it by inheritance.

<<[[Makefile]]>>=
report.txt: summarize
	<<run the report>>
<<run the report>>=
out=report.txt
sh summarize a b c > "$out"
@

\section{Building this document}

A single highlighted, indexed weave exercises all four context rules
and stacks the three relevant scanners:
\begin{verbatim}
noweave -delay -autolang -autodefs python3 -autodefs sh \
    -autodefs make -index \
    -filter 'tominted -lexer noweb_lexer.py' \
    embedded.nw > embedded.tex
pdflatex -shell-escape embedded.tex
\end{verbatim}
The highlighted build needs the one-time [[latexminted]] setup
described in [[README.python]].

